# todo

<!--
  Concept-name substitution point: this skill uses the product-level names
  "Todo" and "Scheduled Task". If the names change (e.g. to "Reminder" or
  "Cron Task"), the rename is mechanical: update this file and the script
  headers only. The JSON field names below do NOT encode concept names.
-->

Use this skill to persist multi-step, time-bound, or cross-heartbeat work.
It provides two concepts:

- **Todo** — a completion-bearing work item with a title, description, a list
  of subtasks, and a `done` boolean. Todos are stored one JSON file per day
  under `todo_list/<YYYYMM>/<DD>.json`. The file path encodes the day — there
  is no `date` field inside a todo.
- **Scheduled Task** — a wake-up configuration with a minute-granular trigger
  time. Stored as a single JSON list in `scheduled_tasks.json`. Has no
  `done` field — it is not a work item, it is a timer that makes the next
  heartbeat a `reminder`-kind heartbeat when its fire minute arrives.

## When to use this skill

Use it when:

- The work is multi-step and you want a durable list you can revisit across
  heartbeats.
- You are making a time-bound commitment (e.g. "do X at 14:00 today" or
  "every Monday at 09:00").
- The work is likely to span more than one heartbeat and you need to avoid
  dropping candidate items at a decision point.

Do NOT use it for:

- One-shot answers to a human question that are resolved in the same
  heartbeat.
- Scratch work that is decided and discarded within a single heartbeat.
- External task-management sync or cross-agent shared lists (out of scope).

## Todo — edit the day's file directly

Todos are edited with the SDK-native Read / Edit / Write tools. There is
no CRUD script between the agent and the todo file. The path is computed
from `now_minute` (see the runtime's time injection):

```
todo_list/<YYYYMM>/<DD>.json
# today example: todo_list/202604/19.json
```

Each file holds a JSON list of Todo objects:

```
{
  "id": "t<n>",
  "title": "string",
  "description": "string (free-form, may be empty)",
  "subtasks": [ { "id": 1, "text": "...", "done": false } ],
  "done": false
}
```

Rules: `id` is `t<n>` where `n` is the next sequential integer within this
day's file. Subtask `id` is a plain sequential integer within its enclosing
todo. No `date`, `reminder_at`, `recurrence`, or `completions` fields on a
Todo — those belong to Scheduled Task.

## Todo — atomic write helper (internal)

Direct Edit/Write is the primary path. This skill also ships a small helper
that appends a new todo to the correct day file using the atomic-rename
pattern — useful when a script or the pre-heartbeat hook needs to enqueue a
todo without opening the file in the agent's tool:

```bash
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/_write_today.py \
    --title "Triage PR queue" \
    --description "Look at the three open PRs on main."
# --date YYYY-MM-DD optional; defaults to today in the agent's tz
# --agent-workdir PATH optional; defaults to the current working directory
# prints the new todo id (e.g. "t1") on stdout
```

This is a utility, not the public surface for agents — an agent that is
doing its own planning should prefer direct Edit/Write on the day file.

## Scheduled Task — dedicated script surface

Scheduled tasks get a dedicated script surface because the reminder
semantics (weekday / date matching, id allocation, delivered-log
maintenance) benefit from one canonical implementation shared between the
agent and the pre-heartbeat hook.

```bash
# Add a weekly scheduled task:
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/add_scheduled.py \
    --title "..." --kind weekly --time HH:MM --weekdays MON,TUE

# Add a one-shot scheduled task:
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/add_scheduled.py \
    --title "..." --kind date --time HH:MM --date YYYY-MM-DD

# List all scheduled tasks:
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/list_scheduled.py

# Delete a scheduled task by id:
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/delete_scheduled.py --id s<n>
```

The pre-heartbeat hook (`pre_heartbeat.py`) that reads `scheduled_tasks.json`
to produce `Runtime/due_reminders.json` is scaffolded separately; it lands
alongside the runtime integration in
`providers/claude/run_claude.py.tmpl` (out of scope for this slice).

## Convenience reader

```bash
uv run python ${CLAUDE_SKILL_DIR}/scripts/fetch_today.py
# prints today's todos (JSON); defaults to today, --date YYYY-MM-DD optional
# --agent-workdir PATH optional; defaults to the current working directory
```

## Storage layout

Per deployed agent, under the agent's workdir:

```
<agent_workdir>/
  todo_list/
    <YYYYMM>/
      <DD>.json        # JSON list of Todo objects for that day
  scheduled_tasks.json # JSON list of Scheduled Task objects
  Runtime/
    due_reminders.json    # (runtime-owned) ids of due reminders for the next heartbeat
    scheduled_delivered.json  # (runtime-owned) "id@now_minute" idempotency log
```

Writes on either side use write-to-tempfile + `os.replace` for atomic
rename — the human-side frontend and the agent can both write to the same
file without corruption.

## Rules

- Todos are edited directly with Read/Edit/Write; only use `_write_today.py`
  when a script-level append is needed (pre-heartbeat hook, smoke test).
- Scheduled tasks MUST be written via the `add_scheduled` / `delete_scheduled`
  scripts — never hand-edit `scheduled_tasks.json` during a heartbeat,
  because the id-allocation and delivered-log invariants depend on the
  scripts.
- `fetch_today.py` is convenience; the agent is free to `cat` the day file
  too.
- Time is taken from `now_minute` injected by the runtime — do not shell out
  to `date` or call `datetime.now()` in agent prompts.
